               <interp inst="t18451027-2163" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18451027"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18451027-2163" type="date" value="18451027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18451027-2163-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2163-18451027 t18451027-2163-offence-1 t18451027-2163-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2163. <persName id="def1-2163-18451027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2163-18451027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2163-18451027" type="surname" value="CHILLINGWORTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2163-18451027" type="given" value="MATTHEW HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MATTHEW HENRY CHILLINGWORTH</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18451027-2163-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18451027-2163-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18451027-2163-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp> was in<lb></lb>dicted for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1178" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1178" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1178" type="surname" value="HAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1178" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the keeper of the Surrey Asylum. I was in<lb></lb>debted</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184510270191"></xptr>
               <p>to Mr. Bennett 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I sent my man with a check of 11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. to pay that—this is the check—my man came back—I received 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in change—that was the amount I ought to have received if the amount I owed to Mr. Bennet had been paid, with the exception of 2 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., which they generally throw off—I have no recollection when I sent the check—it is dated on the 1st of Aug., and I had had it by me some two or three days before I sent it—one Sunday morning, a week or two afterwards, the prisoner came with Harris, who makes out Mr. Bennett's bills—Harris said in the prisoner's presence that there was something wrong about a sovereign that was paid short—he asked me what I had paid—I told him I had given Sharpe, my man, a check for 11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and when be came back he brought me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and the bill receipted—this is the bill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1179" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1179" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1179" type="surname" value="SHARPE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1179" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SHARPE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Mr. Hay—on the 4th of Aug. he sent me with a check—I do not know whether this is the check—it was wrapped in a bit of paper—what Mr. Hay gave me I took to Mr. Bennett's—I gave the check to the prisoner—I did not tell him anything—he got change and gave me the change and this bill—I took it back to my master—there were five sovereigns, and some silver—I did not count the silver.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you any conversation with the prisoner about the amount? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I merely gave him the check in a piece of paper—I counted the sovereigns I received back, but not the silver—I just took what he gave me—I was in Mr. Bennett's shop when I gave the prisoner the check—there were one or two people in the shop—I do not know where he got change for the check—he went out to get it, and came the way of the London-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Whatever money the prisoner gave you, you car<lb></lb>ried to your master? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I carried it all the way in my hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1180" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1180" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1180" type="surname" value="BENNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1180" type="given" value="DEBORAH"></interp>DEBORAH BENNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Solomon Bennett—I recollect, on the 4th of Aug., the prisoner gave me 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and said Mr. Hay bad paid his bill—it might have been about eleven or twelve o'clock in the day—the prisoner then went to the book, and I saw him writedown 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—this is the book, and this is his handwriting, "Hay paid bill, 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In whose handwriting is this bill and receipt? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The items I cannot say—my husband makes out the bills sometimes, and sometimes Harris does—I think this is my husband's writing—my sight is very bad—Mr. Hay owed 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and the prisoner gave me 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I did not know the amount Mr. Hay owed—I am not always in the shop—I know the prisoner brought an action against us.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1181" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1181" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1181" type="surname" value="HARRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1181" type="given" value="NATHAN"></interp>NATHAN HARRIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I have been book-keeper to Mr. Bennett for many years—this bill is my writing—I make out all the bills—Mrs. Bennett knows nothing about them—this receipt to it is the prisoner's writing—on Sunday, the 10th of Aug., I went to the prosecutor's books, as I do every Sunday—no one writes in the ledger but myself—here is the com<lb></lb>mon waste book, and everything that occurs is entered in this—here is another book, in which the entry is made from that common waste-book, and in this it is entered 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., in the prisoner's writing—this is for me to enter into the ledger—this is 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. only, but no shillings; that led to tne finding it out—here is, "Hay paid bill, 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> If you had got the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., you would have been 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. short? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—that caused the finding it out—I said it must have been 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and then it was only 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184510270192"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did you do then? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I went to Mr. Hay, to know what had been paid, and then the prisoner said to me, "Don't say anything to mistress about it; I will try and make it up by next Sunday, and then the books will be all right"—he said he was sorry for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Will you swear that this 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. is the prisoner's writing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Decidedly—if it had been entered 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., I should not have discovered it—I should have taken it for granted that the money had been paid.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1182" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1182" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1182" type="surname" value="BENNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1182" type="given" value="SIMON"></interp>SIMON BENNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's son—he is on the Continent—in consequence of what I heard from Harris, I had some conversation with the prisoner—I asked him what he had received from Mr. Hay—he said, "A cheque for 11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I said "How much did you give my mother?" he said 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and he gave Mr. Hay's man 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I said, "How much do you make that?"—he said, "11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I said, "How do you make that out? it is only 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—he did not know what to say—he seemed very much confused, and did not seem to know how to account for the other 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—his father was going by—I called him in and told him of it—he said, "I am very sorry, Mr. Bennett, but I am not surprised at it; he is a very bad boy; I could have got him into the Post Office"—the prisoner said he did not know how to account for the 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; he must have lost it, and had reckoned it up wrong—I said I did not know what to do in it myself, as my father was on the Continent, and I was not in the business—I consulted with Mr. Harris, and we sent the prisoner away—next morning he entered an action against us—I believe the action was not brought by the prisoner's present attorney—I do not know.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-1183" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1183" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1183" type="surname" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-1183" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES LEWIS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 36). I apprehended the prisoner on the 11th of Aug.—he was given into custody by Harris—he said it was no use, he intended to bring an action against him. On the following day, in going to the police-office, he was met by an acquaintance of his own, who asked him what he had been doing, that he was locked up—he said Bennett's people had locked him up last night—he told him to go and get a solicitor—when he got a little farther, he met another person, who asked him what he was locked up for—he said he had made a mistake in a sovereign, and Bennett's people had locked him up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18451027-2163-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
